		<dc:description id="description"><i>Ghosts</i> is a 3-act tragedy was written in 1881 that centers around a Danish sea captain’s widow who, no matter how she has tried, cannot escape the ghosts of the past.</dc:description>
		<meta property="meta-auth" refines="#description">https://standardebooks.org</meta>
		<meta id="long-description" property="se:long-description" refines="#description">
			&lt;p&gt;Written in 1881, when melodrama and farce were still at their peak of popularity, Ibsen’s &lt;i&gt;Ghosts&lt;/i&gt; is a 3-act tragedy that explores uncomfortable, even forbidden themes and was a highly critical commentary on the morality of the day. The play centers around the widow of a prominent Norwegian sea captain whose son returns home and, with tragic consequences, revives the ghosts of the past that she has long laboured to put to rest.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Ghosts&lt;/i&gt; immediately became a source of controversy for its inclusion of such topics as venereal disease, incest and euthanasia and was banned from being performed in England for many years. Its arrival signals a shift in nature of theatre and, despite negative criticism, was translated into other languages and performed in Sweden, Germany and New York within a few years of its debut. It stands now as one of the works considered to have ushered in the era of modern drama.&lt;/p&gt;
		</meta>
